  <subsection>
    <title>Transformations of graphs</title>
  <p> 
    Transformations of graphs in general are reviewed in <xref ref="sec-func-graphs" />. Here we discuss some transformations specifically in terms of trigonometric functions. 
    
    <example xml:id="trans1">
    <title>Basic transformations GRAPHS NEEDED</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Use a graphing tool to graph <m>y=2\cos x</m> and <m>y=\cos (2x)</m>. How are they different from the graph of <m>y=\cos x</m>?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
INSERT GRAPHS
      </p>
      <p>
      Looking at the graph of <m>y=2\cos x</m>, we see that it looks very similar to the graph of <m>y=\cos x</m>, except that the <m>y</m>-values range between -2 and 2, instead of -1 and 1. 
      </p>
      <p>
      Looking at the graph of <m>y=\cos (2x))</m>, we see that it again looks similar to the graph of <m>y=\cos x</m>, except this time the persiod is <m>\pi</m> instead of <m>2\pi</m>. The oscillations occur `twice as fast' compared to the graph of <m>y=\cos x)</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
    </p>
      <p>
Generalizing what we saw in <xref ref="trans1"/>, the graph of <m>y=A \cos x</m>  (for <m>A \not= 0</m>) oscillates between <m>A</m> and <m>-A</m>. Similarly for the graph of <m>y=A \sin x</m>. The value <m>A</m> is called the <term>amplitude</term> of the sine or cosine curve. 
       </p>
             <p>
The graphs of <m>y=\cos (kx)</m> and <m>y=\sin (kx)</m>  (for <m>k \not= 0</m>) have periods of <m>2\pi /k</m>. This is because compared to <m>y=\cos x</m> and <m>y=\sin x</m>, the graphs of <m>y=\cos (kx)</m> and <m>y=\sin (kx)</m> are compressed horizontally by a factor of <m>k</m>.
  </p>

        <p>
Compared to <m>y=\cos x</m>, the graph of <m>y=\cos (x+c)</m> is shifted <m>c</m> units left if <m>c > 0</m> and right if <m>c</m> is less than 0. Here, <m>c</m> is called the <term>phase shift</term>. 
       </p>

  <p>
     <example xml:id="graph3">
    <title>Amplitude, period, phase shift</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Find the amplitude, period and phase shift for the curve
      <me>
        y = 3 \sin (4x-7)
      </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
          The amplitude is <m>3</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The period is <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The phase shift is <m>\frac{7}{4}</m>.
        </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
       <p>
        The amplitude is given by the constant multiplied by <m>sin \theta</m>, in this case 3. 
       </p>
<p>
  To find the period, notice that compared to <m>y=\sin x</m>, the graph of <m>y = 3 \sin (4x-7)</m> is compressed by a factor of <m>4</m>. This means the period is divided by <m>4</m>. The period of <m>y=\sin x</m> is <m>2\pi</m>, which means the persiod of <m>y = 3 \sin (4x-7)</m> is <m>\frac{2\pi}{4}= \frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
</p>

<p>
  To find the phase shift, we need to consider <m>(4x-7)</m>. It is easier to see the phase shift if we first factor the <m>4</m>:
  <me>
    y = 3 \sin (4x-7) =  3 \sin \left(4\left(x-\frac{7}{4}\right)\right)
  </me>
  Now we see that the curve has been shifted <m>\frac{7}{4}</m> units to the right, so the phase shift is <m>\frac{7}{4}</m>. 
</p>
    </solution>
  </example>
     </p>



